WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.569 --> 00:00:12.920
What's very comfortable now may not be so
comfortable later on.

00:00:12.920 --> 00:00:16.470
That's when I might have to take out my mutual
funds.

00:00:16.470 --> 00:00:19.700
My only worry is my dad works for the state
of Illinois.

00:00:19.700 --> 00:00:20.930
The state's pretty much insolvent.

00:00:20.930 --> 00:00:24.890
And even his health care, which is through
the state of Illinois, it could take up to

00:00:24.890 --> 00:00:31.740
a year for him to get reimbursed for things
like that, so that is worrisome.

00:00:31.740 --> 00:00:41.640
Justine Underhill: Retirement is all some
people ever think about, especially the 50-million-plus

00:00:41.640 --> 00:00:44.620
Americans set to retire in the next few years.

00:00:44.620 --> 00:00:47.790
They obsess over it, like my dad did.

00:00:47.790 --> 00:00:48.790
It's what they worked for.

00:00:48.790 --> 00:00:49.840
It's their dreams.

00:00:49.840 --> 00:00:52.789
But those dreams could be shattered.

00:00:52.789 --> 00:00:56.859
You're about to hear Real Vision's founder
and CEO, Raoul Pal, explore why we're heading

00:00:56.859 --> 00:01:02.379
into a retirement crisis in America and around
the world as many people take on more risk

00:01:02.379 --> 00:01:03.469
than they understand.

00:01:03.469 --> 00:01:07.240
I was curious to see if anyone was thinking
about this, so we spoke with people in New

00:01:07.240 --> 00:01:12.920
York and heard the same story over and over--
people pushing off retirement, people not

00:01:12.920 --> 00:01:16.380
having enough savings, people relying on government
pensions.

00:01:16.380 --> 00:01:17.900
Here's some of what they said.

00:01:17.900 --> 00:01:18.900
No.

00:01:18.900 --> 00:01:21.830
No way I could have saved enough for retirement.

00:01:21.830 --> 00:01:25.270
I mean, I have enough to retire, let's say,
if I want to go to Wyoming or something like

00:01:25.270 --> 00:01:26.270
that.

00:01:26.270 --> 00:01:29.000
I saved enough for at least the next 10 years.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:34.299
Who knows with inflation what will happen,
but I feel the next 10 years, I'm OK.

00:01:34.299 --> 00:01:38.880
If the United States government goes out of
business, then my pension won't be there.

00:01:38.880 --> 00:01:42.540
These stories were just a small sample of
what we heard.

00:01:42.540 --> 00:01:46.009
And this is not just something that those
actively looking for retirement are going

00:01:46.009 --> 00:01:47.009
to face.

00:01:47.009 --> 00:01:50.689
It's something that's going to have a big
impact on my generation as well, whether it's

00:01:50.689 --> 00:01:56.619
figuring out pensions, or social security,
or potentially supporting our own parents'.

00:01:56.619 --> 00:01:59.760
Retirement is part of the promise of life
in the developed world.

00:01:59.760 --> 00:02:04.020
And if that promise isn't met, it's really
going to affect everyone, whether you're hoping

00:02:04.020 --> 00:02:08.580
to retire in 5 years or 50.

00:02:08.580 --> 00:02:18.870
Roaul Pal: My name's Raoul Pal.

00:02:18.870 --> 00:02:22.840
I'm the CEO and co-founder of Real Vision.

00:02:22.840 --> 00:02:27.340
But today, I'm talking on behalf of Global
Macro Investor, my research business.

00:02:27.340 --> 00:02:32.730
I want to talk about what I think is the biggest,
single theme of our generation.

00:02:32.730 --> 00:02:38.109
And I think it's the most important thing
that anybody can understand.

00:02:38.109 --> 00:02:40.880
And it's all about the pension crisis.

00:02:40.880 --> 00:02:45.250
You see, demographics is the big story of
our time.

00:02:45.250 --> 00:02:49.220
And it's all about the story of the baby boomer
generation.

00:02:49.220 --> 00:02:55.180
This was the largest generation of people
the world had ever known in the richest countries

00:02:55.180 --> 00:02:56.970
in across the globe.

00:02:56.970 --> 00:03:05.990
Now, that generation drove all of the macroeconomic
forces that we come to recognize as normal.

00:03:05.990 --> 00:03:11.930
When they first came into the labor force
back in the 1970s when they 20 or so years

00:03:11.930 --> 00:03:16.760
old, what they did was they bid up the demand
for goods.

00:03:16.760 --> 00:03:20.930
Because if you think about it, a record number
of people came in to buy their first suits,

00:03:20.930 --> 00:03:24.799
their first house, their first car, their
first table, their first chair.

00:03:24.799 --> 00:03:26.350
Everything was new.

00:03:26.350 --> 00:03:31.910
That demand created an enormous problem for
the world to deal with, and it created the

00:03:31.910 --> 00:03:33.600
inflationary environment of the '80s.

00:03:33.600 --> 00:03:36.959
Yes, there were monetary reasons behind that
as well.

00:03:36.959 --> 00:03:40.210
But really, a lot of it was driven by demographics.

00:03:40.210 --> 00:03:47.780
Now, as that generation moved through their
lifetimes, they had a particular set of behavior

00:03:47.780 --> 00:03:51.690
patterns that affected the financial world
particularly.

00:03:51.690 --> 00:03:58.370
The main one is the fact that after the second
World War, that young generation decided they

00:03:58.370 --> 00:04:01.340
didn't want to be their parents, as almost
everybody does.

00:04:01.340 --> 00:04:03.959
And they said, we don't want to be austere.

00:04:03.959 --> 00:04:07.350
Their parents had lived through two world
wars.

00:04:07.350 --> 00:04:09.720
What they wanted to do was spend.

00:04:09.720 --> 00:04:13.560
They wanted to be free of the shackles of
the things that their parents had had in the

00:04:13.560 --> 00:04:15.120
past.

00:04:15.120 --> 00:04:21.430
So what happened was Wall Street, being clever
as ever, came up with this genius idea.

00:04:21.430 --> 00:04:22.780
It was the pension plan.

00:04:22.780 --> 00:04:26.990
Now, pension plans had existed for a long
time before.

00:04:26.990 --> 00:04:30.180
But really, this is where the pension plan
became everything.

00:04:30.180 --> 00:04:32.520
Wall Street fed them a story.

00:04:32.520 --> 00:04:34.400
The story was simple.

00:04:34.400 --> 00:04:36.950
You don't need to save as much money as your
parents.

00:04:36.950 --> 00:04:40.720
You don't need to spend or save 20% of your
income.

00:04:40.720 --> 00:04:42.970
What you need to do is give it to us.

00:04:42.970 --> 00:04:47.010
We're the smart guys, and we'll turn into
more money.

00:04:47.010 --> 00:04:49.820
And that means you'll have more money to spend.

00:04:49.820 --> 00:04:55.510
So that started the largest stock market boom
in all of recorded history.

00:04:55.510 --> 00:05:02.170
Now, the other thing that happened is as consumption
became a larger part of the economy-- and

00:05:02.170 --> 00:05:07.720
that was driven by government policy as well--
is the baby boomers were offered another piece

00:05:07.720 --> 00:05:09.830
of magic from Wall Street.

00:05:09.830 --> 00:05:11.410
They were offered credit.

00:05:11.410 --> 00:05:17.500
So in the '80s, Ronald Reagan and Margaret
Thatcher basically allowed credit to be available

00:05:17.500 --> 00:05:18.500
to everybody.

00:05:18.500 --> 00:05:21.680
So suddenly, the credit boom took off.

00:05:21.680 --> 00:05:26.380
So there we have two monetary booms happening
at the same time.

00:05:26.380 --> 00:05:30.770
The baby boomers have stopped saving, have
given a little bit of money from their 401(k)s

00:05:30.770 --> 00:05:33.220
to Wall Street that starts accumulating quickly.

00:05:33.220 --> 00:05:39.930
Their income has also then gone into credit,
the servicing of credit to buy more and more

00:05:39.930 --> 00:05:41.300
goods.

00:05:41.300 --> 00:05:44.150
That trend continued for a long time.

00:05:44.150 --> 00:05:48.400
The trend of consumption within the US economy
continues to this day.

00:05:48.400 --> 00:05:51.810
It's massively outsized because of this credit
boom.

00:05:51.810 --> 00:05:54.740
That meant that Wall Street became outsized
too.

00:05:54.740 --> 00:06:00.520
It was taking the money from the pension system,
and investing that-- or speculating with it--

00:06:00.520 --> 00:06:03.380
and also making money from the credit side.

00:06:03.380 --> 00:06:09.280
Now, that all ended in a complete blow up
that happened in 2008.

00:06:09.280 --> 00:06:11.380
But why did 2000 happen?

00:06:11.380 --> 00:06:15.920
Well, interestingly enough, that's when the
first baby boomers started retiring.

00:06:15.920 --> 00:06:20.620
When they started retiring, suddenly there
were some sellers of stocks.

00:06:20.620 --> 00:06:26.380
Before that, everybody had been buying stocks
every single month in their 401(k).

00:06:26.380 --> 00:06:29.900
Buying-the-dip mentality became the key thing
for the world.

00:06:29.900 --> 00:06:34.430
But the problem is now we're facing the demographic
time bomb.

00:06:34.430 --> 00:06:39.800
I remember when I was back at Goldman Sachs
in the late '90s.

00:06:39.800 --> 00:06:44.050
Some of my colleagues wrote an article called
"The Demographic Time Bomb."

00:06:44.050 --> 00:06:50.900
And that was about the issues the world will
face in the future as retirees start retiring

00:06:50.900 --> 00:06:56.460
and whether the state sector could afford
all of the draw on the capital.

00:06:56.460 --> 00:07:00.210
Now I'm not going to talk about the state
sector in this particular presentation.

00:07:00.210 --> 00:07:05.940
We all know the story that there's too few
millennials and younger people paying into

00:07:05.940 --> 00:07:08.270
the system to pay for these retirees.

00:07:08.270 --> 00:07:11.920
The maths don't add up, so the entitlements
can explode.

00:07:11.920 --> 00:07:15.980
And these numbers can be in the hundreds of
trillions of dollars.

00:07:15.980 --> 00:07:17.790
But I don't want to talk about that.

00:07:17.790 --> 00:07:22.590
I also don't want to talk about the defined
benefit pension system.

00:07:22.590 --> 00:07:26.160
That's another big story that I think many
of you are aware of.

00:07:26.160 --> 00:07:31.820
We've seen it all across America and all across
Europe into the UK where defined benefit pension

00:07:31.820 --> 00:07:37.889
schemes will never be able to afford to pay
out the promises that they had to the retirees.

00:07:37.889 --> 00:07:44.190
You see, the returns in financial markets
weren't quite as good as the snake oil salesman

00:07:44.190 --> 00:07:46.030
on Wall Street told everybody.

00:07:46.030 --> 00:07:47.030
And that was a problem.

00:07:47.030 --> 00:07:48.760
It's kind of like a Ponzi scheme.

00:07:48.760 --> 00:07:51.230
The first people to get out made all the returns.

00:07:51.230 --> 00:07:53.850
The last people to get out get nothing.

00:07:53.850 --> 00:07:55.450
And that's the real issue.

00:07:55.450 --> 00:08:01.990
The real issue is all of this is coming to
a head because everybody is about to retire.

00:08:01.990 --> 00:08:06.780
If you look at the chart of the baby boomers
reaching retirement age, you can see it's

00:08:06.780 --> 00:08:08.540
a demographic wall.

00:08:08.540 --> 00:08:14.310
Currently we're retiring at about 3.9 million
in America alone, baby boomers.

00:08:14.310 --> 00:08:20.330
And it goes up in a straight line all the
way through to 2027.

00:08:20.330 --> 00:08:24.980
What we've got is more and more people, every
year, retiring.

00:08:24.980 --> 00:08:30.550
That is an extraordinary state of affairs
because retirees have a different behavior

00:08:30.550 --> 00:08:32.510
pattern than the average person.

00:08:32.510 --> 00:08:35.860
You can see the chart in a different way here.

00:08:35.860 --> 00:08:41.500
You can see that the average retirement age
is currently around 64 in America.

00:08:41.500 --> 00:08:46.800
And this year, 2018, the average baby boomer
is 64.

00:08:46.800 --> 00:08:52.580
It's telling us the average person is destined
to retire this year.

00:08:52.580 --> 00:08:57.360
But the real question is here-- who can afford
to retire?

00:08:57.360 --> 00:09:04.920
You see, if we look at the retirement age
of Americans, the actual retirement age is

00:09:04.920 --> 00:09:06.590
going up.

00:09:06.590 --> 00:09:11.820
And those who haven't retired, they're deciding
that they're going to have to work longer

00:09:11.820 --> 00:09:12.820
too.

00:09:12.820 --> 00:09:17.900
You see, the real issue here is that people
can't afford to retire.

00:09:17.900 --> 00:09:22.640
So they're having to extend retirement-- either
expected or current retirement dates-- out

00:09:22.640 --> 00:09:24.210
into the future.

00:09:24.210 --> 00:09:28.390
It's this problem of not being able to afford
retirement that is creating the problems we've

00:09:28.390 --> 00:09:29.390
got today.

00:09:29.390 --> 00:09:33.230
The other way you can look at this is when
we look at the labor force participation rate

00:09:33.230 --> 00:09:36.480
of the people above 65 years old.

00:09:36.480 --> 00:09:40.850
Oddly, the 65-year-olds have been coming back
into the labor force at a record rate.

00:09:40.850 --> 00:09:45.020
They're competing for jobs with millennials
and others.

00:09:45.020 --> 00:09:46.250
This is an odd states of affairs.

00:09:46.250 --> 00:09:53.040
And, again, is driven by the issue of these
baby boomers having far too much debt to retire

00:09:53.040 --> 00:09:54.610
and not enough savings.

00:09:54.610 --> 00:09:56.020
So let's drill down to the numbers.

00:09:56.020 --> 00:10:00.170
It's really important to understand the numbers
behind what I'm talking about.

00:10:00.170 --> 00:10:02.029
So let's dig into the stats.

00:10:02.029 --> 00:10:06.370
See, the US average pension benefits are $23,000
a year.

00:10:06.370 --> 00:10:13.960
But there's a bit of an issue because disposable
income per capita is $44,000 a year.

00:10:13.960 --> 00:10:19.320
Now, the ideal retirement income that these
people want obviously matches their disposable

00:10:19.320 --> 00:10:24.149
income, which is about $44,000 to $45,000
a year.

00:10:24.149 --> 00:10:29.670
But really, when you impute from their savings,
what they really get is another $9,000.

00:10:29.670 --> 00:10:39.690
So their total benefits are about $31,000
versus their needs of about $45,000.

00:10:39.690 --> 00:10:41.610
This is a huge problem.

00:10:41.610 --> 00:10:45.899
There's a 30% shortfall in their savings.

00:10:45.899 --> 00:10:48.360
And that has to come out of consumption.

00:10:48.360 --> 00:10:50.880
I think many of you have seen this before.

00:10:50.880 --> 00:10:55.279
It's the household net worth, the average
net worth of the American household.

00:10:55.279 --> 00:10:57.100
And it looks pretty good, right?

00:10:57.100 --> 00:10:59.100
They've got $24,000 in bonds.

00:10:59.100 --> 00:11:02.880
Americans don't seem to like bonds, and that's
something I'll talk about in a bit.

00:11:02.880 --> 00:11:10.690
They've got $269,000 of equities, $300,000
of real estate, savings of $107,000, pension

00:11:10.690 --> 00:11:16.330
fund assets of $264,000, and other savings
and assets of about $120,000.

00:11:16.330 --> 00:11:21.540
Now, that's a pretty healthy million dollar
balance sheet, so what's the problem?

00:11:21.540 --> 00:11:24.480
The problem is it's massively skewed by the
1%.

00:11:24.480 --> 00:11:30.500
That 1% that we hear about versus the 99%,
well, they've got all the assets and all the

00:11:30.500 --> 00:11:31.500
savings.

00:11:31.500 --> 00:11:38.710
When you strip out the data for the 1% and
calculate the median net worth, it's an entirely

00:11:38.710 --> 00:11:40.130
different game.

00:11:40.130 --> 00:11:46.050
The median net worth offers something that
I think is terrifying and sad.

00:11:46.050 --> 00:11:49.550
The average person has $4,000 in their bonds.

00:11:49.550 --> 00:11:56.839
They have $45,000 in equities, $53,000 in
real estate, which is extraordinary, right?

00:11:56.839 --> 00:12:03.890
That is all they have after their mortgage
is $53,000 for a lifetime worth of household

00:12:03.890 --> 00:12:04.890
investment.

00:12:04.890 --> 00:12:12.750
They have savings of $18,000, pension fund
assets of $44,000, and other assets of $20,000.

00:12:12.750 --> 00:12:21.180
You see, the problem is these people are benefiting
from one of the biggest shifts the world has

00:12:21.180 --> 00:12:23.730
ever seen-- life expectancy.

00:12:23.730 --> 00:12:30.300
Life expectancy, although it dropped a couple
of years running recently in the US, is rising.

00:12:30.300 --> 00:12:37.430
So life expectancy in America, and across
the world, is in an exponential trend higher.

00:12:37.430 --> 00:12:40.600
It is going higher and higher every single
year.

00:12:40.600 --> 00:12:45.540
Obviously, the last couple of years were the
opiate epidemic saw a bit of a pullback.

00:12:45.540 --> 00:12:49.910
But generally, the average American doesn't
know how long they're going to live for.

00:12:49.910 --> 00:12:52.000
It's going to be longer than they thought.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:57.340
You see, not knowing how long you're going
to live for changes your behavior pattern.

00:12:57.340 --> 00:13:03.149
It means that you start pushing out your retirement
date because you don't have enough money to

00:13:03.149 --> 00:13:04.339
retire.

00:13:04.339 --> 00:13:08.910
Because if you've moved your life expectancy
on 5 years, well then you need a lot more

00:13:08.910 --> 00:13:09.930
money.

00:13:09.930 --> 00:13:14.980
In a low-interest-rate environment, it becomes
almost impossible to generate the income,

00:13:14.980 --> 00:13:18.770
so you're drawing down on capital very, very
rapidly.

00:13:18.770 --> 00:13:21.950
So let's look at this balance sheet to see
where the capital really is.

00:13:21.950 --> 00:13:28.640
Now, what have to understand is US households
have really taken on board the fact that they're

00:13:28.640 --> 00:13:31.230
going to live longer, and they don't have
enough savings.

00:13:31.230 --> 00:13:36.020
Because after 2000 and 2008, the world hasn't
generated enough returns.

00:13:36.020 --> 00:13:41.220
So what they've done is taken the most amount
of risk possible.

00:13:41.220 --> 00:13:47.279
Normally, if you're about to retire, you should
be increasing your fixed income allocation

00:13:47.279 --> 00:13:50.000
to guarantee your future retirement income.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:56.170
However, behaviorally speaking, if you don't
have a high enough income to retire on, you

00:13:56.170 --> 00:13:58.459
have a kind of shit-or- bust scenario.

00:13:58.459 --> 00:14:00.940
What you have to do is take that risk.

00:14:00.940 --> 00:14:07.890
That risk, for American, is buying real estate,
and they did that in droves back in the 2000s.

00:14:07.890 --> 00:14:13.540
Now, they got burned in that, and they don't
have much net worth left in that any longer.

00:14:13.540 --> 00:14:17.620
So the real driver of net worth has been the
equity market.

00:14:17.620 --> 00:14:23.339
The equity market is the only driver of net
worth going forwards, and this has meant that

00:14:23.339 --> 00:14:26.480
people have doubled up their bets and tripled
up their bets.

00:14:26.480 --> 00:14:32.240
They have this bet directly in equities, and
they have this bet in their pension plans.

00:14:32.240 --> 00:14:36.910
The pension plans themselves have record holding
of equities versus fixed income.

00:14:36.910 --> 00:14:40.830
They also have record risk in terms of credit.

00:14:40.830 --> 00:14:45.940
Private equity, venture capital, hedge funds,
they all have equity-like returns.

00:14:45.940 --> 00:14:47.630
They're risk-seeking investments.

00:14:47.630 --> 00:14:51.250
And they're doing this because nobody can
fund their retirement.

00:14:51.250 --> 00:14:53.530
It's the same story at government level.

00:14:53.530 --> 00:14:57.420
It's the same story at defined benefit pension
level.

00:14:57.420 --> 00:15:01.300
And it's the same story for households and
their 401(k)s.

00:15:01.300 --> 00:15:06.760
Corporate pension plans, they're all the same--
nobody has enough money to fund retirements.

00:15:06.760 --> 00:15:10.899
So everybody is taking the maximum risk.

00:15:10.899 --> 00:15:16.160
Now, in a rising equity market, this kind
of makes sense.

00:15:16.160 --> 00:15:19.649
You're clawing back some of the ability to
retire.

00:15:19.649 --> 00:15:23.490
But if things change, the picture gets a little
bit worse.

00:15:23.490 --> 00:15:29.850
You see, the one bet people are taking is
they're actually putting the maximum allocation

00:15:29.850 --> 00:15:37.120
in all of recorded history, across the entire
system, into risk- seeking, equity-like assets

00:15:37.120 --> 00:15:41.110
when equity valuations are off the charts.

00:15:41.110 --> 00:15:45.990
You see, when we look at the chart of the
median price revenue of the S&amp;P 500, we can

00:15:45.990 --> 00:15:49.870
see it's at all time, ridiculous, record highs.

00:15:49.870 --> 00:15:51.080
We could use any measure.

00:15:51.080 --> 00:15:53.620
I just used this chart because it's the most
dramatic.

00:15:53.620 --> 00:15:55.180
But we can use the P-ratio.

00:15:55.180 --> 00:15:58.030
It'll be the second most overvalued market
in history.

00:15:58.030 --> 00:16:00.820
The median P will be the most overvalued in
history.

00:16:00.820 --> 00:16:03.450
Market cap to GDP, the most overvalued in
history.

00:16:03.450 --> 00:16:07.680
We have an extraordinarily overvalued market.

00:16:07.680 --> 00:16:14.829
Now what's the worst thing about this is that
there is a record over weight of equities.

00:16:14.829 --> 00:16:20.910
Nobody has owned this many equities or equity-like
instruments-- risk- seeking instruments--

00:16:20.910 --> 00:16:24.800
ever before when the valuation is so high.

00:16:24.800 --> 00:16:27.769
That is a dangerous setup.

00:16:27.769 --> 00:16:37.050
You see, the real problem here is it's all
about the business cycle.

00:16:37.050 --> 00:16:40.110
The business cycle, as you know, ebbs and
flows.

00:16:40.110 --> 00:16:41.899
You can see it on the chart here.

00:16:41.899 --> 00:16:47.020
It goes up and down, and it's relatively predictable--
within some boundaries.

00:16:47.020 --> 00:16:54.200
But what happens is a peaking, booming economy
eventually gives way to a recession.

00:16:54.200 --> 00:16:57.990
And they come along periodically-- every 4
to 8 years.

00:16:57.990 --> 00:17:03.990
Now what's interesting about this expansion
is this is the second-equal, longest expansion

00:17:03.990 --> 00:17:06.649
in all economic history.

00:17:06.649 --> 00:17:11.089
And by next month or the month after, this
will be the second longest outright.

00:17:11.089 --> 00:17:18.069
So what that tells you is there is a probability
that this expansion has to end at some point.

00:17:18.069 --> 00:17:20.989
Could it roll on for another couple of years,
2 or 3 years?

00:17:20.989 --> 00:17:22.069
Of course it could.

00:17:22.069 --> 00:17:24.980
Could this end up being the longest ever expansion?

00:17:24.980 --> 00:17:26.240
Of course it can.

00:17:26.240 --> 00:17:33.080
The point being is the clock is ticking, and
it's moving towards the next recession.

00:17:33.080 --> 00:17:36.529
Now, normally, that's no big deal.

00:17:36.529 --> 00:17:38.880
But this time, it's a bit different.

00:17:38.880 --> 00:17:42.580
You see, in recessions, the stock market generally
crashes.

00:17:42.580 --> 00:17:44.029
That's normal.

00:17:44.029 --> 00:17:45.450
Companies earn less money.

00:17:45.450 --> 00:17:48.429
Investors fear worse outcomes than are expected.

00:17:48.429 --> 00:17:50.570
And the market sells off massively.

00:17:50.570 --> 00:17:54.309
And over time, it has had a tendency to recover.

00:17:54.309 --> 00:17:57.710
Well, again, that's a bit of a recency bias.

00:17:57.710 --> 00:18:02.659
Because all across Europe and other markets
around the world, things never did recover.

00:18:02.659 --> 00:18:06.309
And why didn't they recover versus America?

00:18:06.309 --> 00:18:11.669
And that's because the Americans have a cult
of equity, and the Europeans tend to have

00:18:11.669 --> 00:18:13.190
a cult of bonds.

00:18:13.190 --> 00:18:16.659
So Europeans basically gave up on the equity
market.

00:18:16.659 --> 00:18:21.120
The structure of the pension system there
means that they own much less equities.

00:18:21.120 --> 00:18:26.629
They're about 70% or 80% in bonds for this
particular cohort.

00:18:26.629 --> 00:18:28.070
The Americans are the opposite.

00:18:28.070 --> 00:18:31.570
They're about 70% in equity and equity-like
instruments.

00:18:31.570 --> 00:18:34.549
They're taking huge amounts of risk.

00:18:34.549 --> 00:18:41.169
Now, normally, in America with this risk seeking
culture, once the equity market falls, the

00:18:41.169 --> 00:18:46.919
401(k) payments come in as everybody's income
starts filtering into the stock market and

00:18:46.919 --> 00:18:50.350
acts as a break and helps the market rise.

00:18:50.350 --> 00:18:56.769
The problem is the next recession is going
to cross the exact point that the maximum

