The business cycle, as you know, ebbsber of
people are going into retirement.

00:18:59.679 --> 00:19:02.559
This has never happened before anywhere.

00:19:02.559 --> 00:19:08.639
What it means is that all of the life savings
that are in equities, which is basically 70%

00:19:08.639 --> 00:19:14.769
of the entire household balance sheet is going
to get wiped out in one recession.

00:19:14.769 --> 00:19:18.950
And they won't be able to buy back because
they won't have an income to buy back.

00:19:18.950 --> 00:19:24.909
This is the biggest problem I can see in the
world today, and nobody really understands

00:19:24.909 --> 00:19:29.759
that juxtaposition between the business cycle,
risk taking, and demographics.

00:19:29.759 --> 00:19:35.240
It's this Nexus that makes me so concerned
about what is going to happen to this baby

00:19:35.240 --> 00:19:40.289
boom generation unless somebody tells them
about the risks that they're taking.

00:19:40.289 --> 00:19:42.400
Wall Street doesn't want to tell them.

00:19:42.400 --> 00:19:44.999
The asset management firms don't want to tell
them.

00:19:44.999 --> 00:19:49.710
The TV companies don't want to tell them because
everybody's cashing in on the same boom.

00:19:49.710 --> 00:19:55.090
Just look at the amount of advertising based
around asset management and this industry.

00:19:55.090 --> 00:20:00.049
It's terrifying to be pushing people in at
this peak.

00:20:00.049 --> 00:20:02.179
It's OK to trade and invest.

00:20:02.179 --> 00:20:06.629
But if you are of retirement age, you should
be cautious.

00:20:06.629 --> 00:20:10.690
If you're a millennial, you should be the
opposite of cautious.

00:20:10.690 --> 00:20:12.909
You should be waiting for this opportunity.

00:20:12.909 --> 00:20:17.859
So there's behavioral mindset that needs to
take place, but there's more to this.

00:20:17.859 --> 00:20:23.640
You see, demographics also tell us where the
economy is going to go in the future.

00:20:23.640 --> 00:20:28.960
And the reason being is that a number of things
are correlated to demographics because people

00:20:28.960 --> 00:20:32.299
of a certain age generally act in a certain
way.

00:20:32.299 --> 00:20:36.330
That's not to say all generations and all
the age groups act the same.

00:20:36.330 --> 00:20:41.989
But overall, a retiree will spend a lot less
than somebody who is in the peak of their

00:20:41.989 --> 00:20:42.989
earning career.

00:20:42.989 --> 00:20:46.009
I always use the example of my father.

00:20:46.009 --> 00:20:51.230
When my father retired at 60 years old, he
was the kind of guy where we were lucky enough

00:20:51.230 --> 00:20:54.889
to buy a new car every 3 years, and it was
a fancy German car.

00:20:54.889 --> 00:20:58.809
And he'd have nice wine in the house and go
out for dinners all the time.

00:20:58.809 --> 00:21:03.309
Cut forward to retirement, suddenly he had
his fixed investment pull.

00:21:03.309 --> 00:21:04.309
That's what he had to live off.

00:21:04.309 --> 00:21:07.889
He didn't know how long he was going to live
for, and he didn't know what the cost of living

00:21:07.889 --> 00:21:09.289
was going to be.

00:21:09.289 --> 00:21:10.289
So what does he do?

00:21:10.289 --> 00:21:12.580
Pull on the handbrake on his spending.

00:21:12.580 --> 00:21:19.479
Cut forward 5, 6 years, suddenly, I would
say he's spending 60% less than he used to

00:21:19.479 --> 00:21:21.429
spend in a year.

00:21:21.429 --> 00:21:27.119
Now when you multiply that out across the
entire baby boom population, you've got a

00:21:27.119 --> 00:21:30.580
dramatic economic event, and there's no getting
around that.

00:21:30.580 --> 00:21:32.009
This is kind of baked in the cake.

00:21:32.009 --> 00:21:37.389
Let me show you some charts about how demographics
tie into the economy.

00:21:37.389 --> 00:21:41.909
The first chart is the unemployment rate versus
the labor force participation rate.

00:21:41.909 --> 00:21:46.749
Now the labor force participation rate is
key because it's really how many people are

00:21:46.749 --> 00:21:49.999
earning in the labor force to drive the economy.

00:21:49.999 --> 00:21:52.639
Now what's interesting is people have said,
oh, look at this.

00:21:52.639 --> 00:21:53.639
It's amazing.

00:21:53.639 --> 00:21:56.679
The US economy is generating so many jobs.

00:21:56.679 --> 00:21:57.980
Well, it's kind of odd.

00:21:57.980 --> 00:22:02.200
The unemployment rate is low, but the economy
has not generated anything near the number

00:22:02.200 --> 00:22:05.369
of jobs that it has done in previous cycles.

00:22:05.369 --> 00:22:06.820
Why is that?

00:22:06.820 --> 00:22:09.850
It's because people are opting out of the
labor force.

00:22:09.850 --> 00:22:15.059
So it's naturally driving down the unemployment
rate because the labor pool is shrinking.

00:22:15.059 --> 00:22:17.799
So it's a bit of an old indicator.

00:22:17.799 --> 00:22:23.570
This is exactly the reason why the Japanese
have had an incredibly low unemployment rate

00:22:23.570 --> 00:22:29.870
over the entire time of their lackluster,
post-demographic, crash economy.

00:22:29.870 --> 00:22:35.080
It's one of the reasons why the European unemployment
rate has come back sharply.

00:22:35.080 --> 00:22:39.269
It's because of the fact that people opt out
of the labor force.

00:22:39.269 --> 00:22:44.980
Now in America, it means that we should expect
the labor force unemployment rate to fall

00:22:44.980 --> 00:22:46.230
and fall.

00:22:46.230 --> 00:22:50.109
Now that's interesting, and many people say
that's inflationary.

00:22:50.109 --> 00:22:54.539
But it's not because of the number of people
competing for those jobs or deciding to opt

00:22:54.539 --> 00:22:55.539
out.

00:22:55.539 --> 00:22:57.629
Anyway, let's look at some more charts to
build more of a picture.

00:22:57.629 --> 00:23:02.820
As I talked about, the thing I really fear
the most in this whole equation is what happens

00:23:02.820 --> 00:23:04.039
to spending rates.

00:23:04.039 --> 00:23:09.779
You see, the spending rate, the personal consumption
rate, basically follows your age group.

00:23:09.779 --> 00:23:11.600
You spend in a predictable pattern.

00:23:11.600 --> 00:23:12.600
Yes, I know.

00:23:12.600 --> 00:23:13.600
We all think we're individuals.

00:23:13.600 --> 00:23:14.600
But we're actually not.

00:23:14.600 --> 00:23:18.830
We all basically do the same thing as people
of our age, give or take the parameters of

00:23:18.830 --> 00:23:22.240
which we earn and some of the other behavioral
aspects.

00:23:22.240 --> 00:23:26.029
But really speaking, consumption is based
on age.

00:23:26.029 --> 00:23:29.770
And what happens is the older we get, the
less we begin to consume.

00:23:29.770 --> 00:23:35.159
That kind of makes sense because you bought
most of the things you need.

00:23:35.159 --> 00:23:40.359
You tend to buy larger, big-ticket items--
holidays, cars-- when you're older if you've

00:23:40.359 --> 00:23:42.409
still got that kind of income before you retire.

00:23:42.409 --> 00:23:46.720
You see, if you're a bit younger in peak earning,
you tend to buy more things for your house.

00:23:46.720 --> 00:23:51.190
You know, you might buy yourself better bed
coverings, or a new bed, or go to IKEA a bit

00:23:51.190 --> 00:23:52.190
more often.

00:23:52.190 --> 00:23:53.600
You tend to buy yourself a few more luxuries.

00:23:53.600 --> 00:23:56.529
You tend to spend a bit more in the supermarket.

00:23:56.529 --> 00:23:57.639
And that's normal.

00:23:57.639 --> 00:24:00.039
Everybody does the same thing because you're
at peak spending.

00:24:00.039 --> 00:24:03.109
But when you get older, you tend to buy less
of those things.

00:24:03.109 --> 00:24:05.889
You tend to buy more big-ticket items.

00:24:05.889 --> 00:24:08.320
You might buy a nice car.

00:24:08.320 --> 00:24:10.120
You might buy a nice holiday.

00:24:10.120 --> 00:24:12.489
But you've got most of the things you actually
need.

00:24:12.489 --> 00:24:20.379
You've accumulated them across your lifetime,
and your consumption goes down.

00:24:20.379 --> 00:24:25.690
Another fascinating chart is you can see gasoline
retail sales also exactly mirror the labor

00:24:25.690 --> 00:24:27.690
force participation rate.

00:24:27.690 --> 00:24:29.480
Now why the hell is that?

00:24:29.480 --> 00:24:33.970
Because basically the older you get, the less
you consume gasoline.

00:24:33.970 --> 00:24:34.980
You drive less.

00:24:34.980 --> 00:24:36.859
Again, I can use my parents for that.

00:24:36.859 --> 00:24:38.710
They used to drive everywhere.

00:24:38.710 --> 00:24:42.679
They live in Spain, and they would drive across
the country to go and see the place.

00:24:42.679 --> 00:24:46.039
But the older they got, the smaller their
circle got.

00:24:46.039 --> 00:24:50.679
And now, basically, they go to the local supermarket,
to the local bar, to the local restaurant.

00:24:50.679 --> 00:24:52.320
So their mileage goes down.

00:24:52.320 --> 00:24:54.029
They just consume less gas.

00:24:54.029 --> 00:24:56.399
They're not running around as much.

00:24:56.399 --> 00:25:01.169
So interesting enough, the whole of the petrochemical
complex is tied to demographics.

00:25:01.169 --> 00:25:03.610
I bet you didn't know that.

00:25:03.610 --> 00:25:05.639
Also, monetarist talk about the velocity of
money.

00:25:05.639 --> 00:25:10.840
And it's a key indicator for inflation.

00:25:10.840 --> 00:25:14.250
If money is moving around the system, it tends
to be more inflationary.

00:25:14.250 --> 00:25:18.820
It kind of gets around the system a lot more
and creates inflation.

00:25:18.820 --> 00:25:23.570
Now the problem is velocity of money is essentially
a demographic phenomenon.

00:25:23.570 --> 00:25:28.149
The older people get the more they save and
the less they spend, and the money doesn't

00:25:28.149 --> 00:25:29.289
go around the system.

00:25:29.289 --> 00:25:31.289
They're not reinvesting in things.

00:25:31.289 --> 00:25:33.049
They're not spending as much.

00:25:33.049 --> 00:25:36.289
And like consumption, it tends to fall over
time.

00:25:36.289 --> 00:25:39.979
So they're basically a function of each other,
and I think that's really important.

00:25:39.979 --> 00:25:42.529
You can throw in the low interest rates into
this.

00:25:42.529 --> 00:25:47.859
They're all interconnected and tend to drag
down velocity of money, tend to drag down

00:25:47.859 --> 00:25:51.769
the labor force participation rate, tend to
drag down consumption.

00:25:51.769 --> 00:25:54.820
Now I want to give you something new to think
about.

