00:27:11.489 --> 00:27:13.600
we think this is going.

00:27:13.600 --> 00:27:20.359
And then we can look forward and see where
it goes, and this is where things get ugly.

00:27:20.359 --> 00:27:28.440
You see, because of the demographics, the
labor force participation rate is about to

00:27:28.440 --> 00:27:30.419
fall off a cliff.

00:27:30.419 --> 00:27:38.820
Yes, there's a bit of wiggle, but 2018, 2019
is we should see a collapse in labor force

00:27:38.820 --> 00:27:39.820
participation.

00:27:39.820 --> 00:27:41.749
Now, obviously, that kind of makes sense.

00:27:41.749 --> 00:27:46.029
I've told you that we're hitting that point
where the retirement age and the average age

00:27:46.029 --> 00:27:47.580
of Americans are crossing.

00:27:47.580 --> 00:27:50.429
So they're going to start this wall of retirement.

00:27:50.429 --> 00:27:55.120
Now that means that people are coming out
of the labor force, and that has some big

00:27:55.120 --> 00:27:57.559
knock-on effects that you need to be aware
of.

00:27:57.559 --> 00:28:03.650
Now armed with our future labor force participation
rate, we can look where the Fed balance sheet

00:28:03.650 --> 00:28:04.650
is going to go.

00:28:04.650 --> 00:28:06.919
The Fed balance sheet here is inverted.

00:28:06.919 --> 00:28:10.299
It's saying it's going to go to $8 trillion
dollars.

00:28:10.299 --> 00:28:13.760
What's interesting is, again, how great this
fit is.

00:28:13.760 --> 00:28:16.450
And think of the prism I talked about of the
business cycle.

00:28:16.450 --> 00:28:19.289
At some point soon, we're going to have a
recession.

00:28:19.289 --> 00:28:22.929
And soon meaning 1, 2, 3 years.

00:28:22.929 --> 00:28:27.830
Now what we know in the recession is we have
no other outcomes except the Fed expanding

00:28:27.830 --> 00:28:29.240
their balance sheet.

00:28:29.240 --> 00:28:31.799
We've not come up with another way of dealing
with this yet.

00:28:31.799 --> 00:28:33.210
Yes, there's going to be fiscal stuff.

00:28:33.210 --> 00:28:35.330
Yes, there's going to be other untried measures.

00:28:35.330 --> 00:28:38.619
But the Fed are going to expand, whether we
like it or not.

00:28:38.619 --> 00:28:43.679
So this will lead us to expect a massive expansion
in the balance sheet to come to offset this

00:28:43.679 --> 00:28:45.349
wave of retirees.

00:28:45.349 --> 00:28:49.649
Again, what's interesting is a bit of economic
history because Japan has an older population

00:28:49.649 --> 00:28:50.729
by 10 years.

00:28:50.729 --> 00:28:57.450
So if we look at the BOJ balance sheet and
look at the Fed balance sheet now as a percentage

00:28:57.450 --> 00:29:01.940
of GDP and put them against each other, it's
very clear where this is going to go.

00:29:01.940 --> 00:29:07.179
It's telling us we're going to see an absolute
explosion of the balance sheet as a percentage

00:29:07.179 --> 00:29:08.749
of GDP over time.

00:29:08.749 --> 00:29:11.220
Now I'm not going to get into the ramifications
of that.

00:29:11.220 --> 00:29:13.580
It's something we've discussed on Real Vision
a lot.

00:29:13.580 --> 00:29:16.999
We kind of know it's coming, and there's a
number of ways it will get dealt with.

00:29:16.999 --> 00:29:22.710
But the point being is that demographics are
pretty much dyed in the wool right now.

00:29:22.710 --> 00:29:26.850
And if they're dyed in the wool, then we know
where personal consumption is going.

00:29:26.850 --> 00:29:32.769
Personal consumption is going to unwind the
great boom of the last 30 or 40 years where

00:29:32.769 --> 00:29:37.610
consumption became over 75% of the US economy.

00:29:37.610 --> 00:29:41.929
Consumption is going to shrink as a percentage
of the economy, and consumption itself is

00:29:41.929 --> 00:29:43.490
going to go negative.

00:29:43.490 --> 00:29:46.770
Now that is something nobody is set up to
understand.

00:29:46.770 --> 00:29:52.419
Can you imagine a world where consumption
is the net takeaway from the economy and not

00:29:52.419 --> 00:29:53.700
the driver?

00:29:53.700 --> 00:29:55.210
That's what we're setting up for.

00:29:55.210 --> 00:29:57.519
This is something truly extraordinary.

00:29:57.519 --> 00:30:00.809
Now, again, go back to the big cycle.

00:30:00.809 --> 00:30:05.090
To drive consumption further, you're going
to have to ram the millennial generation with

00:30:05.090 --> 00:30:09.690
enormous amounts of debt to drive consumption
and offset some of this.

00:30:09.690 --> 00:30:11.389
But they don't want to do that.

00:30:11.389 --> 00:30:14.379
They're already saddled with debt from their
education.

00:30:14.379 --> 00:30:17.849
So they don't have the ability to do anything
about this.

00:30:17.849 --> 00:30:18.919
They also don't earn enough.

00:30:18.919 --> 00:30:22.379
They're not offsetting the same amount of
wealth as their parents.

00:30:22.379 --> 00:30:27.100
There is a mismatch here, so don't expect
the millennials to save the day.

00:30:27.100 --> 00:30:30.080
There is a mismatch of an age gap.

00:30:30.080 --> 00:30:36.200
It will come out eventually, and I'll talk
a bit about that in due course.

00:30:36.200 --> 00:30:41.759
You see, the equity market is also a function
of demographics.

00:30:41.759 --> 00:30:45.480
Now the chart's are a bit noisier because
equities are a much noisier instrument than

00:30:45.480 --> 00:30:50.679
most others because they're built on fear
and greed, almost more than any other asset

00:30:50.679 --> 00:30:51.679
class.

00:30:51.679 --> 00:30:56.859
But equities should follow the returns offered
by the labor force participation rate.

00:30:56.859 --> 00:31:03.549
An aging population obviously needs to sell
equities to realize income to retire and live

00:31:03.549 --> 00:31:04.549
off.

00:31:04.549 --> 00:31:06.599
There is no way around that situation.

00:31:06.599 --> 00:31:11.299
They will have to sell equities, and they
will sell as many equities as they can into

00:31:11.299 --> 00:31:15.549
the next recession because, behaviorally,
they need to protect themselves.

00:31:15.549 --> 00:31:20.360
They will become more risk adverse than any
generation in history at that point when the

00:31:20.360 --> 00:31:23.070
recession comes and the market sells off.

00:31:23.070 --> 00:31:29.480
It is just tied in to human behavior, and
that means that the returns on the S&amp;P are

00:31:29.480 --> 00:31:31.950
going to be somewhat problematic.

00:31:31.950 --> 00:31:38.769
And not just a sell off and a rally back afterwards,
but a more extended downturn in the future

00:31:38.769 --> 00:31:44.340
returns of equities and potential, long-term,
compounding, negative returns, which is something

00:31:44.340 --> 00:31:46.869
many other countries with aging populations
have seen.

00:31:46.869 --> 00:31:50.379
But the US has not seen it yet, and doesn't
believe it can happen.

00:31:50.379 --> 00:31:55.429
If you think all the things I told you about
consumption, about gasoline sales-- I've told

00:31:55.429 --> 00:32:01.690
you about what's going to happen to equities--
what that also means is inflation is almost

00:32:01.690 --> 00:32:04.339
impossible to generate.

00:32:04.339 --> 00:32:07.070
It's impossible because people cannot consume
enough.

00:32:07.070 --> 00:32:12.869
The millennials do not offset the largest
spending generation of all history.

00:32:12.869 --> 00:32:15.379
So what you get is a falling of inflation.

00:32:15.379 --> 00:32:22.379
This is why I'm a dyed-in-the-wool reflationist,
and I remain so until something dramatic changes.

00:32:22.379 --> 00:32:27.409
Sure, we could see the end of globalization,
and maybe that could change the structure.

00:32:27.409 --> 00:32:31.919
But I think the slow decline in globalization
is not going to do that.

00:32:31.919 --> 00:32:40.349
So I fear that this incredible fit of inflation
and the births as a percentage of the total

00:32:40.349 --> 00:32:45.559
population-- i.e. the aging of the population--
is going to hold true for a long time to come.

00:32:45.559 --> 00:32:53.089
And that means people have wrongly allocated
in risk-seeking assets versus bonds for example.

00:32:53.089 --> 00:32:59.549
It just makes the world understand that fearing
cash is not the worst thing.

00:32:59.549 --> 00:33:05.230
You see, CPI really is just a reflection of
births as a percentage of the total population.

00:33:05.230 --> 00:33:09.909
I.e. the less people are getting born, the
less inflation is going forward.

00:33:09.909 --> 00:33:12.659
So that's the whole trend going forwards.

00:33:12.659 --> 00:33:15.309
And it says inflation's not coming back.

00:33:15.309 --> 00:33:17.279
It's not something we should fear.

00:33:17.279 --> 00:33:18.820
We shouldn't fear bonds.

00:33:18.820 --> 00:33:23.129
Yes, there is some elements of inflation,
and we're not going to hide from the fact

00:33:23.129 --> 00:33:25.669
that inflation's strangely calculated.

00:33:25.669 --> 00:33:29.789
And that certain things have seen huge inflation,
such as rents and health care.

00:33:29.789 --> 00:33:34.019
And other things have seen huge deflation,
such as the price of Real Vision.

00:33:34.019 --> 00:33:38.179
But there's a number of things that balance
that out, and you've seen the Million Prices

00:33:38.179 --> 00:33:39.179
Project.

00:33:39.179 --> 00:33:44.359
It tells you that broad inflation is not really
there, and it is driven by this phenomena

00:33:44.359 --> 00:33:48.589
of age and demographics.

00:33:48.589 --> 00:33:53.980
So this is why this is the biggest story in
the world.

00:33:53.980 --> 00:34:01.409
We have the richest generation in all history,
by all measures, but with the median person

00:34:01.409 --> 00:34:08.639
with no savings, with too much risk-taking
investments, way too many equities versus

00:34:08.639 --> 00:34:14.470
fixed income or any other investment-- and
certainly over cash-- at the point in the

00:34:14.470 --> 00:34:19.419
business cycle that is getting mature and
we're waiting for the next recession to roll

00:34:19.419 --> 00:34:20.750
along.

00:34:20.750 --> 00:34:25.840
When that recession comes, it's going to half
equity prices-- or more.

00:34:25.840 --> 00:34:29.220
This is the most overvalued stock market in
history.

00:34:29.220 --> 00:34:35.790
And therefore, we should expect the price
of equities to fall significantly.

00:34:35.790 --> 00:34:40.890
That leaves a huge hole in the balance sheet
of all of those people, the biggest group

00:34:40.890 --> 00:34:43.820
on earth ever to retire.

00:34:43.820 --> 00:34:46.899
They won't be able to buy equities to buy
the dip.

00:34:46.899 --> 00:34:48.370
They'll have gone.

00:34:48.370 --> 00:34:53.200
The gen-xers and millennials can't afford
to buy that dip.

00:34:53.200 --> 00:34:58.830
This is a huge risk to the largest generation
of all time.

00:34:58.830 --> 00:35:03.210
And it's something people need to be massively
aware of.

00:35:03.210 --> 00:35:07.300
You need to think really hard about the risks
you're taking this late in the cycle.

00:35:07.300 --> 00:35:12.300
I completely understand you might not have
the money to be able to retire.

00:35:12.300 --> 00:35:16.980
But it's better to have what little you have
now than have half of this later.

00:35:16.980 --> 00:35:20.130
It's something you really have to think about.

00:35:20.130 --> 00:35:25.030
Now many of you will think about, well, how
are the government going to stop this?

00:35:25.030 --> 00:35:27.300
And how the Federal Reserve going to stop
this?

00:35:27.300 --> 00:35:29.700
And they will try because they have to.

00:35:29.700 --> 00:35:32.640
And this is where some of the problems lie.

00:35:32.640 --> 00:35:37.700
If you believe in free markets, the right
answer would be for that baby boom generation

00:35:37.700 --> 00:35:43.430
to pass their wealth on to their kids, either
via inheritance or by transfer of assets at

00:35:43.430 --> 00:35:45.710
a low price that the kids can buy.

00:35:45.710 --> 00:35:50.880
So that's the accumulation of equities at
lower prices that the baby boomers had in

00:35:50.880 --> 00:35:52.740
the '70s and '80s.

00:35:52.740 --> 00:35:58.310
Particularly in the early '80s when they really
started buying equities, Ps we're below 10,

00:35:58.310 --> 00:36:02.010
8, 7, 6-- a lifetime opportunity.

00:36:02.010 --> 00:36:07.020
The millennials faced with the same investing
set right now have an all time record over

00:36:07.020 --> 00:36:14.560
evaluated stock market, an all time record
valuation bond market, all time overvalued

00:36:14.560 --> 00:36:15.560
real estate market.

00:36:15.560 --> 00:36:21.370
They have nowhere to invest that has a positive
rate of return over the next 5 or 10 years.

00:36:21.370 --> 00:36:23.740
It is a stupid point for them to invest.

00:36:23.740 --> 00:36:26.210
What they need is lower prices in all of these.

00:36:26.210 --> 00:36:29.650
The baby boomers should supply it in a free
market.

00:36:29.650 --> 00:36:31.950
But it's unlikely to happen.

00:36:31.950 --> 00:36:35.850
The Federal Reserve are like to step in the
way and increase the balance sheets I showed

00:36:35.850 --> 00:36:36.850
you.

00:36:36.850 --> 00:36:41.660
They're likely to be buying stocks, buying
pension assets, stopping those pension assets

00:36:41.660 --> 00:36:42.970
go plummeting.

00:36:42.970 --> 00:36:46.690
Now that means that the stock market gets
supported.

00:36:46.690 --> 00:36:51.580
The Fed start owning the equity market, exactly
as the Japanese have done.

00:36:51.580 --> 00:36:55.610
But it means that the young generation can't
buy them because they're too expensive.

00:36:55.610 --> 00:37:00.240
What happens to the real estate market, is
that the clearing mechanism-- possibly.

00:37:00.240 --> 00:37:04.630
Or do the baby boomers and millennials end
up living together?

00:37:04.630 --> 00:37:06.950
I think that's the most likely outcome.

00:37:06.950 --> 00:37:11.670
That's what the pre-war generation did, and
that's maybe how this will all end up is we

00:37:11.670 --> 00:37:14.700
have larger households of more household members.

00:37:14.700 --> 00:37:20.420
And I think that would make certain sense
to society, and would free up a bit of savings,

00:37:20.420 --> 00:37:26.260
and would help counteract the loss of savings
that the baby boomers are going to have.

00:37:26.260 --> 00:37:28.770
You see, this is a really tricky world to
navigate.

00:37:28.770 --> 00:37:33.930
And I think you really all need to think hard
and fast about what you're going to do and

00:37:33.930 --> 00:37:36.080
the plans you have.

00:37:36.080 --> 00:37:42.300
There are also financial market people that
said there are opportunities in this.

00:37:42.300 --> 00:37:46.390
Although, it makes me feel a bit grim to say
there's an opportunity in what I see as the

00:37:46.390 --> 00:37:50.460
biggest crisis a generation has ever faced
in financial terms.

00:37:50.460 --> 00:37:52.330
And it's not a bank crash.

00:37:52.330 --> 00:37:57.250
It's a systemic loss of savings from everybody.

00:37:57.250 --> 00:37:58.250
But there are opportunities.

00:37:58.250 --> 00:38:03.141
Because, you see, once you understand the
world through a behavioral standpoint, you

00:38:03.141 --> 00:38:08.580
understand that different people faced with
different issues will behave differently.

00:38:08.580 --> 00:38:11.630
And that means they will change how they spend.

00:38:11.630 --> 00:38:15.020
We've already seen this in the restaurant
sector.

00:38:15.020 --> 00:38:19.631
As the baby boomers are moving towards retirement,
they're starting to spend less in restaurants.

00:38:19.631 --> 00:38:22.980
Restaurants have really struggled in recent
years.

00:38:22.980 --> 00:38:24.480
They've been firing people.

00:38:24.480 --> 00:38:28.020
They have had less profits than they've seen
for a while.

00:38:28.020 --> 00:38:30.290
They've been in and out of recession.

00:38:30.290 --> 00:38:34.740
We've seen it in a number of consumption areas
within the economy that there is a problem

00:38:34.740 --> 00:38:40.230
as these people are starting to finally save
as much as they can before they go into retirement.

00:38:40.230 --> 00:38:43.550
But it does mean they'll do certain things.

00:38:43.550 --> 00:38:45.210
And I call this Boomerville.

00:38:45.210 --> 00:38:49.360
It's the world to understand when people retire.

00:38:49.360 --> 00:38:55.290
You see, go again back to that chart of the
net worth of the median household.

00:38:55.290 --> 00:38:57.560
They have $53,000 in their house.

00:38:57.560 --> 00:39:00.510
So are they supposed to sell their house?

00:39:00.510 --> 00:39:05.790
That basically gets them to live for another
year and a bit.

00:39:05.790 --> 00:39:08.090
Don't forget, they wanted $45,000 a year.

00:39:08.090 --> 00:39:13.110
The house only gives them $52,000 of equity.

00:39:13.110 --> 00:39:18.070
So with this so few savings and this little
cash, what will they do?

00:39:18.070 --> 00:39:23.020
Well, you see, there's a different consumption
pattern that's going to come.

00:39:23.020 --> 00:39:25.310
And it's a slightly grim consumption pattern.

00:39:25.310 --> 00:39:31.810
If you also think about why the middle of
America was so pissed off is because they

00:39:31.810 --> 00:39:36.610
didn't participate in a lot of the final stages
of what is going on.

00:39:36.610 --> 00:39:41.820
The closer you are to that median person,
the further away you are from any boom.

00:39:41.820 --> 00:39:47.760
And you see, if we understand how those people
live now-- the really neglected from society--

00:39:47.760 --> 00:39:53.030
it is actually the leading indicator of where
many more people will need to go.

00:39:53.030 --> 00:39:54.030
And that's sad.

00:39:54.030 --> 00:40:02.260
It's going to increase, probably, populism
within the economy and certainly a bifurcation

00:40:02.260 --> 00:40:07.350
of politics even further than we've seen today
because it's going to be tough on people.

00:40:07.350 --> 00:40:10.370
Dining is going to go towards fast food.

00:40:10.370 --> 00:40:15.120
It's still sadly true that it's easier and
cheaper to get food from McDonald's than it

00:40:15.120 --> 00:40:17.350
is to cook yourself.

00:40:17.350 --> 00:40:19.480
That hits supermarket sales.

00:40:19.480 --> 00:40:22.830
That hits a number of people, particularly
the restaurant industry.

00:40:22.830 --> 00:40:26.340
But it keeps fast food sales ticking along
nicely.

00:40:26.340 --> 00:40:31.730
It's the cheapest way for the masses to afford
to eat, and that's not good for the overall

00:40:31.730 --> 00:40:33.610
health of the population.

00:40:33.610 --> 00:40:39.250
It could, actually, reduce the life expectancy
of the population too and continue to drive

00:40:39.250 --> 00:40:41.080
the obesity epidemic.

00:40:41.080 --> 00:40:42.910
It's really not good.

00:40:42.910 --> 00:40:48.770
Now if you think about the $52,000 in the
house, well, that basically gets you to buy

00:40:48.770 --> 00:40:50.130
a trailer park.

00:40:50.130 --> 00:40:54.990
Now trailer parks become very interesting
for people because they can get rid of the

00:40:54.990 --> 00:40:59.700
debt around a house, own the assets of a trailer
park, and release some cash.

00:40:59.700 --> 00:41:01.990
So owning a trailer is a key thing.

00:41:01.990 --> 00:41:06.200
Now, trailer parks, I think are already high
yielding investments.

00:41:06.200 --> 00:41:08.850
You can get basically 18% returns.

00:41:08.850 --> 00:41:15.100
And there's a listed trailer park business
owned by Sam Zell that I think is an interesting

00:41:15.100 --> 00:41:16.100
play here.

00:41:16.100 --> 00:41:19.460
There's a number of ways of playing this downsizing
of housing.

00:41:19.460 --> 00:41:21.820
But it is an important feature that's to come.

00:41:21.820 --> 00:41:26.790
And again, it's less of the Mac mansions and
the other things that we saw in 2007.

00:41:26.790 --> 00:41:31.810
It's just anybody trying to realign equity
from their regular homes.

00:41:31.810 --> 00:41:33.950
The other thing are cars.

00:41:33.950 --> 00:41:38.670
Nobody is ever going to buy a new one again,
none of this generation will.

00:41:38.670 --> 00:41:41.180
They will keep onto their car as long as possible.

00:41:41.180 --> 00:41:48.100
We saw this a long time ago in Germany where
your average car turnovers were every 3 or

00:41:48.100 --> 00:41:49.660
4 years people buy a new car.

00:41:49.660 --> 00:41:52.500
It then moved to 8,9, 10 years.

00:41:52.500 --> 00:41:53.500
It's my father.

00:41:53.500 --> 00:41:58.420
You know, that guy, my dad, hasn't changed
his car for the last 15 years now.

00:41:58.420 --> 00:42:00.330
That is going to be very common.

00:42:00.330 --> 00:42:04.360
The used car dealership market, yeah, that's
OK.

00:42:04.360 --> 00:42:06.400
It's not so bad.

00:42:06.400 --> 00:42:10.120
But still not good because people are still
not buying as many new cars.

00:42:10.120 --> 00:42:11.520
There's a big problem.

00:42:11.520 --> 00:42:15.700
The entire world is betting that China is
going to take up the demand from the baby

00:42:15.700 --> 00:42:16.700
boomers.

00:42:16.700 --> 00:42:18.150
I'm not so sure about that.

00:42:18.150 --> 00:42:21.850
What we do know is the millennial generation
currently is less interested by cars.

00:42:21.850 --> 00:42:27.380
So they're more likely buyers of secondhand
bangers than they are buying new cars.

00:42:27.380 --> 00:42:31.260
They don't see the status symbol involved
that older generations did.

00:42:31.260 --> 00:42:37.420
But anyway, the point here is the consumption
pattern of America and Europe is changing,

00:42:37.420 --> 00:42:39.790
and it's going to change dramatically.

00:42:39.790 --> 00:42:43.770
That's going to change the investment philosophy
and where you could hide in the stock market

00:42:43.770 --> 00:42:47.520
that's going to be under stress or where you
can find real opportunities.

00:42:47.520 --> 00:42:51.810
I do think that it is going to drive bond
yields lower.

00:42:51.810 --> 00:42:55.150
I think most of you know my view on bonds.

00:42:55.150 --> 00:42:57.940
Unless something changes, demographics will
trump all.

00:42:57.940 --> 00:43:01.791
The other thing we need to think about, many
of us watching Real Vision, is we are part

00:43:01.791 --> 00:43:03.020
of the financial industry.

00:43:03.020 --> 00:43:09.270
You see, the financial industry was one of
the biggest secular booms of all time.

00:43:09.270 --> 00:43:12.580
It was driven by this baby boom generation.

00:43:12.580 --> 00:43:18.090
When they took on debt, it created an enormous
amount of opportunity and a swelling of the

00:43:18.090 --> 00:43:20.390
financial system.

00:43:20.390 --> 00:43:26.370
When they invested in pensions and the 401(k)
system was created, it created an asset boom

00:43:26.370 --> 00:43:27.370
that spread.

00:43:27.370 --> 00:43:32.840
That asset boom, between those 2 building
blocks, went into the hedge fund industry.

00:43:32.840 --> 00:43:37.890
They went into the private equity industry,
the venture capital industry, the real estate

00:43:37.890 --> 00:43:38.890
industry.

00:43:38.890 --> 00:43:45.430
Everything we understand as the asset management
industry was driven by these people.

00:43:45.430 --> 00:43:48.870
And these people are going to take their money
out.

00:43:48.870 --> 00:43:56.560
That is an enormous change and the final return
to trend for the economy and its outsized

00:43:56.560 --> 00:43:58.530
financial industry.

00:43:58.530 --> 00:44:00.580
We're all seeing it in the financial world.

00:44:00.580 --> 00:44:01.960
We've all seen the banks shrinking.

00:44:01.960 --> 00:44:07.700
We've also seen things like the robotization
within the industry and the changes taking

00:44:07.700 --> 00:44:08.910
place.

00:44:08.910 --> 00:44:14.580
We've seen the disruptors, the vultures hanging
around the system like Bitcoin, Ethereum picking

00:44:14.580 --> 00:44:17.100
at the carcass of the financial industry.

00:44:17.100 --> 00:44:18.330
It's true it's going to change.

00:44:18.330 --> 00:44:20.230
Now, it will adapt.

00:44:20.230 --> 00:44:23.060
Some of the smartest people in the world are
in that industry.

00:44:23.060 --> 00:44:24.060
They will adapt.

00:44:24.060 --> 00:44:25.060
They will change fast.

00:44:25.060 --> 00:44:29.080
Looking how firms like Goldman are adapting
their business model is breathtaking in its

00:44:29.080 --> 00:44:30.080
speed.

00:44:30.080 --> 00:44:33.700
It's at startup speed change that they're
doing stuff.

00:44:33.700 --> 00:44:36.510
But there are other things that are going
to happen, too.

00:44:36.510 --> 00:44:42.000
All of the people in the industry are going
to have to think, how do I get the millennial?

00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:44.920
And how do I get them to invest their life
savings?

00:44:44.920 --> 00:44:47.660
Now, they're right.

00:44:47.660 --> 00:44:51.210
They need to invest savings to save for their
future.

00:44:51.210 --> 00:44:54.820
But they were wrong in how they made it before.

00:44:54.820 --> 00:44:59.260
They made false promises to a generation of
which they couldn't keep.

00:44:59.260 --> 00:45:01.710
This time around, they get to wipe the slate
clean.

00:45:01.710 --> 00:45:05.520
Or they get to defer the blame on somebody
else.

00:45:05.520 --> 00:45:07.410
Let's call it the robo advisors.

00:45:07.410 --> 00:45:08.410
It's not our fault.

00:45:08.410 --> 00:45:10.530
The algorithm gave it to us this way.

00:45:10.530 --> 00:45:12.370
So that's something we need to think about.

00:45:12.370 --> 00:45:16.610
And the industry needs to manage that messaging
unless it wants to get held to blame again

00:45:16.610 --> 00:45:18.950
some point down the future.

00:45:18.950 --> 00:45:22.930
But the real opportunities may lie with the
future of the financial industry.

00:45:22.930 --> 00:45:29.370
Again, if you remember, this millennial generation
is faced with the all time record valuations

00:45:29.370 --> 00:45:34.730
of equities, bonds, real estate, private equity,
pretty much anywhere.

00:45:34.730 --> 00:45:38.130
There is no opportunity for them to buy assets.

00:45:38.130 --> 00:45:39.930
Yes, of course, you could buy gold.

00:45:39.930 --> 00:45:40.930
That's cheap.

00:45:40.930 --> 00:45:42.650
Some commodities are relatively cheap.

00:45:42.650 --> 00:45:49.150
But commodities tend to be more cyclical than
secular, and that becomes somewhat of an issue

00:45:49.150 --> 00:45:51.840
when you're trying to build long term wealth.

00:45:51.840 --> 00:45:56.010
The right answer is for young people to build
businesses.

00:45:56.010 --> 00:45:58.290
The startup culture is exploding.

00:45:58.290 --> 00:46:00.260
This is incredibly important.

00:46:00.260 --> 00:46:02.610
This is the structure of the future economy.

00:46:02.610 --> 00:46:07.490
If you can shift from a financial economy
to an entrepreneurship-based economy, you'll

00:46:07.490 --> 00:46:13.510
build an agile, nimble, and developing economy
that looks for opportunity and generates GDP

00:46:13.510 --> 00:46:14.510
growth.

00:46:14.510 --> 00:46:15.860
It may not employ as many people.

00:46:15.860 --> 00:46:19.460
That's fine because so many people are leaving
the labor force.

00:46:19.460 --> 00:46:24.360
So I'm really encouraged about the startup
and entrepreneurship culture that's generating

00:46:24.360 --> 00:46:28.550
around the world and resonating everywhere
from the Middle East to India, from America

00:46:28.550 --> 00:46:29.550
to Berlin.

00:46:29.550 --> 00:46:32.060
It's everywhere, and I love that.

00:46:32.060 --> 00:46:36.360
The other thing is the crypto space and the
blockchain space.

00:46:36.360 --> 00:46:41.870
Now, this is slightly contentious, but it's
something I've been mulling in my head.

00:46:41.870 --> 00:46:48.640
If you think about that problematic allocation
to all of the other assets, and you have something

00:46:48.640 --> 00:46:54.130
like a cryptocurrency or a set of cryptocurrencies,
